  <section class="page">
    <p class="section-kicker">Rollout Plan</p>
    <h2>Recommended Implementation Approach</h2>
    <p class="lead">
      The best rollout is staged. Start small, prove value, train teams, then expand into deeper workflows and multiple
      branches.
    </p>
    <div class="flow">
      <div class="flow-step"><span>1</span><strong>Discovery</strong>Menu, roles, channels, table flow, delivery model.</div>
      <div class="flow-step"><span>2</span><strong>Setup</strong>Profile, menu, staff, assistant, POS views.</div>
      <div class="flow-step"><span>3</span><strong>Pilot</strong>Test selected orders or tables with staff feedback.</div>
      <div class="flow-step"><span>4</span><strong>Launch</strong>Publish QR links, train staff, promote direct ordering.</div>
      <div class="flow-step"><span>5</span><strong>Optimize</strong>Review KPIs, offers, loyalty, payments, branches.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="grid-2" style="margin-top: 14px;">
      <div class="card">
        <h3>Required for launch</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Final menu with prices and categories.</li>
          <li>Restaurant timings, address, service area, contact details.</li>
          <li>Staff roles for admin, waiter, kitchen, delivery.</li>
          <li>Telegram/WhatsApp ordering channel and QR placement plan.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <h3>Recommended for growth</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>First-time and repeat-customer offer strategy.</li>
          <li>Kitchen preparation time targets.</li>
          <li>Delivery assignment rules.</li>
          <li>Weekly review of orders, AOV, top dishes, and feedback.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="footer-note"><span>Dzukku Business Brochure</span><span>Implementation</span></div>
  </section>

  <section class="page">
    <p class="section-kicker">Client Confidence</p>
    <h2>Common Business Questions</h2>
    <div class="grid-2">
      <div class="card"><h3>Is this only a chatbot?</h3><p>No. Chat is the customer entry point. The platform also includes POS, KDS, tables, reservations, invoices, delivery workflows, and analytics.</p></div>
      <div class="card"><h3>Can non-technical staff use it?</h3><p>Yes. Staff use role-based screens, so each team sees the workflow that matches their daily responsibilities.</p></div>
      <div class="card"><h3>Will it replace Swiggy or Zomato?</h3><p>Not necessarily. Aggregators are useful for discovery. Dzukku is best for direct ordering, repeat customers, and restaurant-owned operations.</p></div>
      <div class="card"><h3>Can it support multiple branches?</h3><p>Yes. The platform can grow into separate menus, staff, customers, orders, dashboards, and AI personalities by branch.</p></div>
      <div class="card"><h3>How do we measure success?</h3><p>Track direct orders, chat conversion, repeat customers, average order value, kitchen time, cancellations, and customer feedback.</p></div>
      <div class="card"><h3>What should we launch first?</h3><p>Start with one outlet, one menu, one ordering channel, one dashboard, and one kitchen queue. Expand after the workflow is proven.</p></div>
    </div>
    <div class="callout">
      Consultant recommendation: begin with a controlled pilot for repeat customers. Prove direct ordering and kitchen
      visibility first, then expand into loyalty, payments, delivery automation, and multi-branch reporting.
    </div>
    <div class="footer-note"><span>Dzukku Business Brochure</span><span>Client Questions</span></div>
  </section>

